Smooth Curve
A BRIEF HISTORY OF GAMS
Generalized Additive Models were introduced in the late 1980s as a way to add flexibility
to traditional regression models. Trevor Hastie and Robert Tibshirani developed the
framework to allow each predictor in a model to follow its own smooth pattern rather
than forcing everything into a straight line.
Through the 1990s and early 2000s, the approach grew in popularity in fields that needed
interpretable models, including public health, ecology, and social sciences.
A major step forward came with the development of the mgcv package in R, created by
Simon Wood. His work added modern smoothing techniques, automatic penalty
selection, and faster computation, making GAMs practical for large and noisy datasets.
Today, GAMs are widely used in finance, fraud detection, risk scoring, and other areas
where organizations need both predictive accuracy and clear explanations.

GAM MODELING OVERVIEW
GAMs extend traditional regression
Capture nonlinear predictor-response relationships
Use spline-based smooth functions
Combine continuous + categorical predictors
Fit with mgcv (penalized splines + GCV)
Model outputs interpretable smooth effects
Goal: Estimate probability of fraud

Data cleansing + encoding

Specify GAM structure (smooths, factors, link function)
Fit model using mgcv
Evaluate using AUC, accuracy, recall
Interpret smooth plots
Predict on test data
GAM EQUATION EXPLAINED
GAM formula:
( g(E[Y]) = \beta_0 + f_1(X_1) + f_2(X_2) + + f_p(X_p) )
(g) = link function (logit for binary fraud)
Smooth functions capture nonlinear effects
Additive contributions from each predictor
Balances flexibility + interpretability
GAM ASSUMPTIONS (FRAUD CONTEXT)
Logit link approximates fraud probability
Additive and independent predictor effects
Smooth, gradual functional relationships
Binomial response distribution
Independent observations
Low predictor multicollinearity
Penalization prevents overfitting

Dataset Description
What It Is
A synthetic dataset built to mimic real financial transactions
Privacy-safe: no real peoples data used
Hosted on Kaggle
Why We Use It
Train fraud detection models for binary classification tasks
Spot fraud: each transaction labeled as fraud (1) or not fraud (0)
What Makes It Special
Realistic fraud patterns:
oGroups of fraudulent transactions
oSubtle, hard-to-notice anomalies
oOdd user behaviors
Large & diverse records: balances normal vs. rare fraud cases addresses class imbalance.
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART I
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART1
Key Characteristics
What's Inside
50,000 Rows: A good amount of data to work with.
Two Labels: Every transaction is marked as either:
o1 = Fraud
o0 = Not Fraud
Data Features-- 21 features across three categories:
Numbers: Like transaction amounts, risk scores, account balances.
Categories: Transaction types (payment, transfer, withdrawal), device types, merchant
categories.
Time Data: When transactions happened (time, day) and their sequence.
Label Distribution
Class Imbalance: Fraudulent transactions are a small percentage, reflecting real-world
scenarios.
Behavioral Realism: Includes unusual spending, behavioral signals, and high-risk profiles.
Modeling flexibility: supports interpretable (GAMs, logistic regression) or high-performance
(XGBoost) approaches
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART11
Visualizations
The charts (including Tables 1, 2, and 3) show that all categories in the dataset
transaction types, device types, and merchant groups are almost perfectly
balanced. Each transaction type has about 12,500 cases, each device type around
16,60016,800, and each merchant category close to 10,000. This even distribution
makes it simple to compare counts and spot patterns. Generalized Additive Models
(GAMs) are still a strong choice because they can handle both numbers and
categories, and capture complex, nonlinear relationships in the data.
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART11
Distribution of Variables
Figure 1. Histograms show key variables
used in fraud detection. Most features
Account_Balance, Transaction_Distance,
Risk_Score, and Card_Ageappear
uniformly distributed, supporting nonlinear
modeling such as GAM.
Transaction_Amount is strongly right-
skewed, with many small transactions and a
few large outliers, indicating that extreme
amounts may signal potential fraud. This
skewness suggests that transformations
(e.g., log-scale) or nonlinear models like
GAM can better capture fraud patterns
and improve prediction accuracy.
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART11
Figure 2 shows that most cards are new, and
older cards are less common. Older cards
may be more at risk because their security
features may be outdated, while newer cards
may have different usage patterns, like more
digital transactions. These differences suggest
that fraud risk changes with card age, and
models like GAM can help capture those
patterns.
DATA EXPLORATION AND VISUALIZATION PART11
Figure 3 shows that fraud
probability changes in a nonlinear
way with transaction amount.
Small payments usually have low
risk, while very large amounts show
higher risk. This makes transaction
amount a key predictor and
shows why GAMs are useful
they can flexibly capture these
curved patterns.

We performed several diagnostic tests
to ensure the model met the
assumptions required for using a GAM.
Most importantly, the Residuals vs
Fitted plot showed no major patterns,
and the Normal QQ plot indicated
only minor tail deviations; both
supporting that the model is
appropriately specified.
These checks confirm the model is not
missing key structure, the residuals
behave as expected, and the results
we interpret from the GAM are
reliable.

LIMITATIONS, INSIGHTS & NEXT STEPS
Limitations:
Synthetic dataset limits real-world generalizability
Class imbalance affects recall for rare fraud case
More complex models may improve accuracy
Insights & Future Work
